00:44:28,458 --> 00:44:29,858
of the vector along the curve.

1160
00:44:30,398 --> 00:44:30,978
Now,

1161
00:44:30,978 --> 00:44:31,938
I'll just remind you,

1162
00:44:32,018 --> 00:44:35,098
we defined the geodesic last time

1163
00:44:35,098 --> 00:44:38,278
by saying this curve is a geodesic

1164
00:44:38,278 --> 00:44:42,418
if the covariant derivative of the tangent vector is zero.

1165
00:44:43,918 --> 00:44:45,938
So let's just put that down.

1166
00:44:46,038 --> 00:44:47,018
Let's write that down,

1167
00:44:47,138 --> 00:44:49,598
the condition for a geodesic.

1168
00:44:51,118 --> 00:44:53,778
v now is going to be replaced

1169
00:44:56,138 --> 00:44:58,738
by dxm by ds.

1170
00:44:58,738 --> 00:45:00,378
In other words,

1171
00:45:00,378 --> 00:45:02,538
we're going to replace v by the tangent vector itself.

1172
00:45:03,238 --> 00:45:05,118
And then the derivative of the

1173
00:45:05,118 --> 00:45:06,998
tangent vector with respect to s

1174
00:45:06,998 --> 00:45:08,358
becomes a second derivative.

1175
00:45:08,918 --> 00:45:12,138
d second xm by ds squared

1176
00:45:13,938 --> 00:45:16,878
plus gamma mnp.

1177
00:45:17,598 --> 00:45:19,318
Now the tangent vector,

1178
00:45:19,518 --> 00:45:21,138
now v is the tangent vector,

1179
00:45:21,318 --> 00:45:23,598
so that's dxn by ds,

1180
00:45:24,477 --> 00:45:26,318
and then dxp by ds.

1181
00:45:31,518 --> 00:45:32,078
Now,

1182
00:45:32,078 --> 00:45:34,698
if the covariant derivative

1183
00:45:35,478 --> 00:45:37,618
of the tangent vector is equal to zero,

1184
00:45:37,738 --> 00:45:38,098
if,

1185
00:45:38,098 --> 00:45:41,758
I'm not saying it's always true for any curve,

1186
00:45:42,038 --> 00:45:43,728
but if the curve is

1187
00:45:43,728 --> 00:45:45,418
chosen so that the covariant derivative

1188
00:45:45,418 --> 00:45:47,818
of the tangent vector is zero,

1189
00:45:47,978 --> 00:45:51,598
then the curve is a geodesic.

1190
00:45:51,638 --> 00:45:52,558
In a sense,

1191
00:45:52,558 --> 00:45:54,878
it's the straightest possible kind of curve

1192
00:45:54,878 --> 00:45:56,678
that you can have in the space.

1193
00:45:57,357 --> 00:45:59,098
If it's flat space,

1194
00:45:59,458 --> 00:46:02,418
then the geodesics are just straight lines.

1195
00:46:03,018 --> 00:46:05,338
If the space is a sphere,

1196
00:46:05,598 --> 00:46:08,138
then the geodesics are great circles.

1197
00:46:08,638 --> 00:46:09,738
In general,

1198
00:46:09,738 --> 00:46:11,598
they're nothing of the sort.

1199
00:46:11,818 --> 00:46:14,738
They're curves that go through the space,

1200
00:46:14,878 --> 00:46:16,878
but they're the straightest possible curves.

1201
00:46:17,398 --> 00:46:19,898
They're the curves you would get by just focusing

1202
00:46:19,898 --> 00:46:21,958
and going incrementally straight ahead.

1203
00:46:24,098 --> 00:46:24,698
Okay.

1204
00:46:24,698 --> 00:46:27,018
But now let's define something else.

1205
00:46:27,138 --> 00:46:30,218
Let's define parallel transport of a vector.

1206
00:46:32,058 --> 00:46:33,358
Supposing we have some vector

1207
00:46:33,358 --> 00:46:35,098
which is not the tangent vector now.

1208
00:46:35,198 --> 00:46:37,838
Let's come back to a general vector like this.

1209
00:46:39,658 --> 00:46:41,858
This vector may not be the tangent vector.

1210
00:46:42,638 --> 00:46:43,598
Here it is.

1211
00:46:43,698 --> 00:46:44,118
It's v.

1212
00:46:47,478 --> 00:46:50,078
And it's allowed to vary along the curve.

1213
00:46:51,458 --> 00:46:52,018
Well,

1214
00:46:52,018 --> 00:46:54,598
if this covariant derivative

1215
00:46:54,598 --> 00:46:55,698
is equal to zero,

1216
00:46:58,138 --> 00:47:00,738
then we say that that vector

1217
00:47:02,338 --> 00:47:05,618
has been transported parallel to itself

1218
00:47:06,438 --> 00:47:07,478
along the curve.

1219
00:47:08,118 --> 00:47:09,218
In other words,

1220
00:47:09,218 --> 00:47:10,938
this is as close as you can get

1221
00:47:10,938 --> 00:47:14,378
to saying the vector is constant along the curve.

1222
00:47:16,298 --> 00:47:19,578
If its covariant derivative along the curve

1223
00:47:19,578 --> 00:47:20,518
is equal to zero,

1224
00:47:20,758 --> 00:47:24,538
one says that this vector

1225
00:47:24,598 --> 00:47:28,778
has been parallelly transported along the curve.

1226
00:47:29,778 --> 00:47:30,298
Okay.

1227
00:47:30,418 --> 00:47:31,598
Can we always do that?

1228
00:47:31,718 --> 00:47:33,698
Can we always take a vector at this end

1229
00:47:33,698 --> 00:47:36,318
and parallel transport it?

1230
00:47:36,398 --> 00:47:36,878
In other words,

1231
00:47:36,878 --> 00:47:38,418
can we take a vector at this end

1232
00:47:38,418 --> 00:47:40,798
and now move it along here in such a way

1233
00:47:40,798 --> 00:47:45,058
that it remains in this sense parallel to itself?

1234
00:47:45,658 --> 00:47:46,178
Yeah,

1235
00:47:46,178 --> 00:47:46,878
we can.

1236
00:47:48,318 --> 00:47:51,258
Let's just rewrite this slightly differently.

1237
00:47:51,518 --> 00:47:52,538
Let's just write this.

1238
00:47:52,538 --> 00:47:56,018
The small change in vm

1239
00:47:56,178 --> 00:47:59,218
as we move from one point to another

1240
00:47:59,218 --> 00:48:00,858
Let's get rid of the ds.

1241
00:48:00,938 --> 00:48:02,618
Just multiply through on both sides.

1242
00:48:03,098 --> 00:48:06,258
The small change in vm is minus

1243
00:48:06,258 --> 00:48:13,178
gamma mnp vn dxp.

1244
00:48:13,978 --> 00:48:18,918
So if I have a small incremental distance,

1245
00:48:19,158 --> 00:48:20,398
dxp here,

1246
00:48:23,438 --> 00:48:24,418
oh sorry,

1247
00:48:24,418 --> 00:48:25,518
this should be a minus sign,

1248
00:48:25,518 --> 00:48:25,818
right?

1249
00:48:26,918 --> 00:48:28,018
Not equal to zero.

1250
00:48:30,638 --> 00:48:31,218
dvm,

1251
00:48:31,218 --> 00:48:33,998
all I've done is solve this equation here,

1252
00:48:34,038 --> 00:48:35,438
multiply through by ds,

1253
00:48:35,438 --> 00:48:36,158
that's not important.

1254
00:48:36,478 --> 00:48:39,638
And this tells me how I should vary

1255
00:48:39,638 --> 00:48:41,238
the components of vm

1256
00:48:41,238 --> 00:48:43,738
as I move along the curve

1257
00:48:44,497 --> 00:48:48,518
so that the covariant derivative is zero.

1258
00:48:49,238 --> 00:48:50,298
In other words,

1259
00:48:50,398 --> 00:48:51,968
this tells me how to

1260
00:48:51,968 --> 00:48:53,538
move from one point to another.

1261
00:48:53,618 --> 00:48:55,178
It tells me how to change v,

1262
00:48:55,878 --> 00:48:57,238
the components of v,

1263
00:48:57,298 --> 00:49:01,378
given the components of v at a starting point

1264
00:49:02,398 --> 00:49:03,998
and the Christoffel symbols

1265
00:49:04,798 --> 00:49:07,218
and the little differential displacement dx,

1266
00:49:07,338 --> 00:49:08,918
it tells me how to

1267
00:49:08,918 --> 00:49:10,498
change v to the next point.

1268
00:49:11,158 --> 00:49:11,978
In fact,

1269
00:49:11,978 --> 00:49:12,638
it tells me,

1270
00:49:12,638 --> 00:49:14,638
once I've updated it from here to here,

1271
00:49:14,798 --> 00:49:16,818
I can do it again and again and again.

1272
00:49:17,698 --> 00:49:20,078
And so it's always possible,

1273
00:49:21,178 --> 00:49:25,118
to choose the components of v along the curve

1274
00:49:25,898 --> 00:49:28,758
so that the covariant derivative is equal to zero.

1275
00:49:29,478 --> 00:49:31,418
All you have to do is to solve

1276
00:49:31,418 --> 00:49:34,438
for how vm changes as you move along the curve

1277
00:49:34,438 --> 00:49:36,758
by knowing that at any one point

1278
00:49:36,758 --> 00:49:37,888
you can find out how

1279
00:49:37,888 --> 00:49:39,018
it moves to the next point,

1280
00:49:39,018 --> 00:49:39,678
and so forth.

1281
00:49:40,198 --> 00:49:41,278
So that's not hard.

1282
00:49:41,638 --> 00:49:45,618
That's the construction and the definition

1283
00:49:45,618 --> 00:49:49,978
of parallelly transporting a vector along a curve.

1284
00:49:49,978 --> 00:49:52,558
To move it from one place to another,

1285
00:49:53,618 --> 00:49:55,118
you just change v

1286
00:49:57,058 --> 00:49:59,658
by an amount that's proportional to v

1287
00:49:59,658 --> 00:50:01,088
and that's proportional to the

1288
00:50:01,088 --> 00:50:02,518
amount that you're displacing it

1289
00:50:02,518 --> 00:50:05,398
and is proportional to the Christoffel symbols.

1290
00:50:05,798 --> 00:50:08,278
Parallel to itself.

1291
00:50:10,978 --> 00:50:11,978
Parallel to itself.

1292
00:50:12,758 --> 00:50:13,798
In other words,

1293
00:50:13,798 --> 00:50:14,958
you have some curve in space,

1294
00:50:15,658 --> 00:50:16,818
I have a vector,

1295
00:50:16,818 --> 00:50:18,198
and I want to move

1296
00:50:18,198 --> 00:50:19,578
it along the curve in space,

1297
00:50:19,578 --> 00:50:22,538
so that it always stays parallel to itself.

1298
00:50:24,218 --> 00:50:25,598
That's what we're trying to do.

1299
00:50:26,058 --> 00:50:26,538
Okay?

1300
00:50:30,018 --> 00:50:31,378
Just a little aside.

1301
00:50:31,758 --> 00:50:34,978
I always like the Hot Wheels car example.

1302
00:50:35,378 --> 00:50:36,638
If you have a globe,

1303
00:50:36,818 --> 00:50:39,798
and you move a Hot Wheels car along it,

1304
00:50:39,838 --> 00:50:41,718
so that the direction never changes,

1305
00:50:41,718 --> 00:50:42,818
you get the great circle.

1306
00:50:43,598 --> 00:50:45,278
Or even on an inner tube,

1307
00:50:45,798 --> 00:50:47,438
the Hot Wheels car is the

1308
00:50:47,438 --> 00:50:49,078
thing that always has the same direction,

1309
00:50:49,078 --> 00:50:50,877
and it will give you the shortest distance.

1310
00:50:51,078 --> 00:50:52,238
That'll give you geodesics.

1311
00:50:52,397 --> 00:50:52,617
Right.

1312
00:50:53,038 --> 00:50:54,298
But now we're taking a

1313
00:50:54,298 --> 00:50:55,558
curve which is not a geodesic.

1314
00:50:55,558 --> 00:50:56,058
First of all,

1315
00:50:56,058 --> 00:50:57,578
a geodesic is a curve,

1316
00:50:57,698 --> 00:51:00,357
is a vector which has been moved parallel to itself.

1317
00:51:00,818 --> 00:51:02,418
I was just using that as an example

1318
00:51:02,418 --> 00:51:03,758
as keeping the same direction

1319
00:51:03,758 --> 00:51:05,098
is the same as minimizing distance.

1320
00:51:06,038 --> 00:51:07,238
That's for a geodesic,

1321
00:51:07,238 --> 00:51:07,357
yeah.

1322
00:51:07,758 --> 00:51:09,498
But you can also parallel transport

1323
00:51:09,498 --> 00:51:11,238
something which is not a geodesic.

1324
00:51:11,238 --> 00:51:11,637
For example,

1325
00:51:12,318 --> 00:51:12,978
we can parallel,

1326
00:51:12,978 --> 00:51:13,778
sorry,

1327
00:51:13,877 --> 00:51:15,207
you can transport a vector

1328
00:51:15,207 --> 00:51:16,538
which is not the tangent vector.

1329
00:51:17,598 --> 00:51:21,038
I want to transport this vector along that line.

1330
00:51:21,318 --> 00:51:23,208
Now if I take that vector

1331
00:51:23,208 --> 00:51:25,098
and transport it along that line,

1332
00:51:26,517 --> 00:51:29,638
then the tangent vector is the thing that I'm transporting.

1333
00:51:30,118 --> 00:51:32,718
If the derivative of the tangent vector is zero,

1334
00:51:32,858 --> 00:51:33,738
it's a straight line.

1335
00:51:34,158 --> 00:51:37,458
But I can also take any vector,

1336
00:51:38,538 --> 00:51:41,138
which is not necessarily a tangent vector,

1337
00:51:41,318 --> 00:51:44,758
and start transporting it along the curve,

1338
00:51:45,058 --> 00:51:46,518
whether or not the tangent vector is a tangent vector,

1339
00:51:46,538 --> 00:51:47,818
or whether or not the curve is a geodesic.

1340
00:51:47,818 --> 00:51:48,938
Take any curve,

1341
00:51:49,118 --> 00:51:50,538
any curve,

1342
00:51:51,338 --> 00:51:52,238
take a vector,

1343
00:51:52,918 --> 00:51:56,418
and transport it so that it stays parallel to itself.

1344
00:51:58,798 --> 00:52:00,198
That you can always do.

1345
00:52:00,338 --> 00:52:03,718
Parallel to itself and of the same magnitude.

1346
00:52:05,058 --> 00:52:07,168
Now would this be the same as

1347
00:52:07,168 --> 00:52:09,278
saying that the angle between the vector

1348
00:52:09,278 --> 00:52:13,098
and the tangent vector is always constant?

1349
00:52:13,278 --> 00:52:13,558
No.

1350
00:52:13,678 --> 00:52:15,498
That's definitely not what it says.

1351
00:52:16,538 --> 00:52:16,618
Why?

1352
00:52:17,498 --> 00:52:20,198
Because the tangent vector is itself changing.

1353
00:52:20,458 --> 00:52:21,978
Let's do it a little differently.

1354
00:52:22,118 --> 00:52:22,258
Here,

1355
00:52:22,258 --> 00:52:24,338
let's take a circle.

1356
00:52:25,378 --> 00:52:27,418
And let's take a vector.

1357
00:52:27,498 --> 00:52:28,038
There's a vector.

1358
00:52:28,278 --> 00:52:30,098
Now I'm going to transport it along itself.

1359
00:52:31,558 --> 00:52:33,858
I'm going to transport it parallel to itself.

1360
00:52:34,158 --> 00:52:36,458
I'm having trouble keeping it exactly parallel.

1361
00:52:36,598 --> 00:52:38,478
But notice by the time it gets down to here,

1362
00:52:39,278 --> 00:52:40,938
it's become the tangent vector.

1363
00:52:42,118 --> 00:52:43,878
Keeping it parallel to itself,

1364
00:52:44,598 --> 00:52:45,838
along the circle,

1365
00:52:46,538 --> 00:52:48,498
will make it the tangent vector over here.

1366
00:52:48,638 --> 00:52:51,178
Over here it's perpendicular to the tangent vector.

1367
00:52:51,418 --> 00:52:53,638
And up here it's the tangent vector again.

1368
00:52:56,138 --> 00:52:57,498
So if I take a circle,

1369
00:52:57,638 --> 00:52:58,938
in flat space,

1370
00:52:59,138 --> 00:53:00,198
a flat space circle,

1371
00:53:00,438 --> 00:53:03,158
and transport a vector parallel to itself,

1372
00:53:03,398 --> 00:53:06,058
the angle relative to the curve changes.

1373
00:53:08,978 --> 00:53:14,878
It's the angle relative to the neighbor

1374
00:53:14,878 --> 00:53:16,238
which hasn't changed.

1375
00:53:17,058 --> 00:53:19,358
The neighbor to this point,

1376
00:53:19,398 --> 00:53:20,718
or to the vector over here,

1377
00:53:20,778 --> 00:53:21,798
is this point over here.

1378
00:53:22,858 --> 00:53:25,558
It's relative to the neighboring value

1379
00:53:25,558 --> 00:53:26,918
that it hasn't changed.

1380
00:53:27,478 --> 00:53:29,538
So we're moving it along incrementally,

1381
00:53:30,278 --> 00:53:31,278
along the curve,

1382
00:53:31,398 --> 00:53:32,198
crazy directions,

1383
00:53:32,638 --> 00:53:35,458
but always keeping it parallel to

1384
00:53:35,458 --> 00:53:37,818
its neighboring value.

1385
00:53:38,278 --> 00:53:40,238
That's called parallel transport.

1386
00:53:41,418 --> 00:53:41,748
Yeah?

1387
00:53:42,318 --> 00:53:43,658
S of ds is any parameter.

1388
00:53:43,998 --> 00:53:46,518
S of ds could be any parameter along the curve.

1389
00:53:46,518 --> 00:53:46,978
Right.

1390
00:53:47,118 --> 00:53:49,218
It's canceled out of this equation here.

1391
00:53:49,338 --> 00:53:49,898
Right.

1392
00:53:50,598 --> 00:53:51,198
Right.

1393
00:53:51,258 --> 00:53:54,258
So there's a notion of parallel transport

1394
00:53:54,258 --> 00:53:55,698
along a curve.

1395
00:53:56,898 --> 00:53:57,498
Okay?

1396
00:53:57,578 --> 00:53:59,738
But now you could ask an interesting question.

1397
00:54:02,058 --> 00:54:02,658
Supposing...

1398
00:54:03,938 --> 00:54:05,818
Does everybody understand what it means?

1399
00:54:06,218 --> 00:54:08,718
It means as you move along the curve,

1400
00:54:08,858 --> 00:54:10,418
even if the curve is turning,

1401
00:54:10,558 --> 00:54:16,238
you make sure that the vector stays parallel to itself.

1402
00:54:16,518 --> 00:54:17,408
Let me give you an

1403
00:54:17,408 --> 00:54:18,298
example how you could do that,

1404
00:54:18,957 --> 00:54:20,738
physically in the real world.

1405
00:54:20,978 --> 00:54:22,098
A gyroscope.

1406
00:54:22,298 --> 00:54:23,498
You take a gyroscope.

1407
00:54:23,758 --> 00:54:25,498
A gyroscope is a spinning object.

1408
00:54:25,998 --> 00:54:26,518
All right?

1409
00:54:26,618 --> 00:54:29,418
If you don't really forcibly change its direction

1410
00:54:29,418 --> 00:54:32,118
and you just hold it by

1411
00:54:32,118 --> 00:54:34,818
its tip or whatever it is,

1412
00:54:34,878 --> 00:54:36,018
and you move it around,

1413
00:54:36,358 --> 00:54:38,038
it will always face in the same direction.

1414
00:54:38,478 --> 00:54:40,398
You don't have to move it along a straight line.

1415
00:54:40,518 --> 00:54:41,898
You can move it along a curve.

1416
00:54:43,017 --> 00:54:44,898
That gyroscope will transport

1417
00:54:45,437 --> 00:54:46,498
parallel to itself.

1418
00:54:46,518 --> 00:54:52,598
So a gyroscope is a physical implementation

1419
00:54:52,598 --> 00:54:56,038
of parallel transport in space along a curve.

1420
00:54:57,158 --> 00:54:57,778
Okay?

1421
00:54:57,878 --> 00:54:59,078
You move it around.

1422
00:55:00,958 --> 00:55:02,698
Pay no attention to it.

1423
00:55:02,758 --> 00:55:03,958
Just move the tip of it.

1424
00:55:04,058 --> 00:55:07,218
And because of its angular momentum,

1425
00:55:07,438 --> 00:55:09,538
it will continue to point in the same direction.

1426
00:55:10,058 --> 00:55:13,378
Even if you transport it along the wildest,

1427
00:55:13,378 --> 00:55:14,238
wiggliest curve,

1428
00:55:15,238 --> 00:55:16,498
that's the idea of parallel transport.

1429
00:55:16,518 --> 00:55:19,318
So this would be the equation then

1430
00:55:19,318 --> 00:55:20,858
that would govern,

1431
00:55:21,078 --> 00:55:22,978
in three dimensions for example,

1432
00:55:23,238 --> 00:55:25,438
would govern the components

1433
00:55:26,428 --> 00:55:28,687
of the axis of a gyroscope

